16/// A `@bytes.View` represents a view into a section of a `Bytes` without copying the data.
17///
18/// # Example
19/// 
20/// ```
21/// let bs = b"\x00\x01\x02\x03\x04\x05"
22/// let bv = bs[1:4]
23/// assert_eq!(bv.length(), 3)
24/// assert_eq!(bv[0], b'\x01')
25/// assert_eq!(bv[1], b'\x02')
26/// assert_eq!(bv[2], b'\x03')
27/// ```

56///|
57/// Retrieves a byte from the view at the specified index.
58///
59/// Parameters:
60///
61/// * `self` : The bytes view to retrieve the byte from.
62/// * `index` : The position in the view from which to retrieve the byte.
63///
64/// Returns the byte at the specified index.
65///
66/// Throws a runtime error if the index is out of bounds (negative or greater
67/// than or equal to the length of the view).
68///
69/// Example:
70///
71/// ```moonbit
72/// test "View::op_get" {
73///   let bytes = b"\x01\x02\x03\x04\x05"
74///   let view = bytes[1:4] // view contains [0x02, 0x03, 0x04]
75///   inspect!(view[1], content="b'\\x03'")
76/// }
77/// 
78/// test "panic View::op_get/out_of_bounds" {
79///   let view = b"\x01\x02\x03"[:]
80///   ignore(view[3]) // Index out of bounds
81/// }
82/// ```
83pub fn 
struct View {
  bytes: Bytes
  start: Int
  len: Int
}
A @bytes.View represents a view into a section of a Bytes without copying the data.
Example
let bs = b"\x00\x01\x02\x03\x04\x05"
let bv = bs[1:4]
assert_eq!(bv.length(), 3)
assert_eq!(bv[0], b'\x01')
assert_eq!(bv[1], b'\x02')
assert_eq!(bv[2], b'\x03')

}

92///|
93/// Retrieves a byte at the specified index from a bytes view without performing
94/// bounds checking.
95///
96/// Parameters:
97///
98/// * `self` : The bytes view to retrieve the byte from.
99/// * `index` : The position in the view from which to retrieve the byte. The
100/// index is relative to the start of the view, not the underlying bytes.
101///
102/// Returns a single byte from the specified position in the view.
103///
104/// Throws a panic if the index is out of bounds (less than 0 or greater than or
105/// equal to the length of the view).
106///
107/// Example:
108///
109/// ```moonbit
110/// test "View::unsafe_get" {
111///   let bytes = b"\x01\x02\x03\x04\x05"
112///   let view = bytes[2:4] // view contains [0x03, 0x04]
113///   inspect!(view.unsafe_get(0), content="b'\\x03'")
114/// }
115/// 
116/// test "panic View::unsafe_get/out_of_bounds" {
117///   let view = b"\x01\x02\x03"[:]
118///   ignore(view.unsafe_get(3)) // Panic: index out of bounds
119/// }
120/// ```
121///
122/// @alert unsafe "Panic if index is out of bounds"
123pub fn 
struct View {
  bytes: Bytes
  start: Int
  len: Int
}
A @bytes.View represents a view into a section of a Bytes without copying the data.
Example
let bs = b"\x00\x01\x02\x03\x04\x05"
let bv = bs[1:4]
assert_eq!(bv.length(), 3)
assert_eq!(bv[0], b'\x01')
assert_eq!(bv[1], b'\x02')
assert_eq!(bv[2], b'\x03')
View::
(View, Int) -> Byte
Retrieves a byte at the specified index from a bytes view without performing
bounds checking.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The bytes view to retrieve the byte from.
    • 

  • index : The position in the view from which to retrieve the byte. The
index is relative to the start of the view, not the underlying bytes.
    • 

Returns a single byte from the specified position in the view.
Throws a panic if the index is out of bounds (less than 0 or greater than or
equal to the length of the view).
Example:
test "View::unsafe_get" {
  let bytes = b"\x01\x02\x03\x04\x05"
  let view = bytes[2:4] // view contains [0x03, 0x04]
  inspect!(view.unsafe_get(0), content="b'\\x03'")
}

test "panic View::unsafe_get/out_of_bounds" {
  let view = b"\x01\x02\x03"[:]
  ignore(view.unsafe_get(3)) // Panic: index out of bounds
}

to_uint64() 
(UInt64, Int) -> UInt64
Performs a bitwise left shift operation on an unsigned 64-bit integer.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 64-bit integer to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift : The number of positions to shift the bits to the left. Must be
between 0 and 63 inclusive, values outside this range will be masked with &  63.
    • 

Returns the result of shifting self left by shift positions. For each
position shifted, the rightmost bit is filled with 0, and the leftmost bit is
discarded.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_shl" {
  let x = 1UL
  inspect!(x << 3, content="8") // 1 shifted left by 3 positions becomes 8
  inspect!(x << 63, content="9223372036854775808") // 1 shifted left by 63 positions
}

303/// Converts an 8-byte sequence to an unsigned 64-bit integer using little-endian
304/// byte order. Each byte in the view is treated as an 8-bit unsigned integer and
305/// combined to form the final 64-bit value, with the least significant byte
306/// first.
307///
308/// Parameters:
309///
310/// * `bytes_view` : A view into a byte sequence that must be exactly 8 bytes
311/// long. Each byte represents one byte of the resulting 64-bit integer, with the
312/// first byte being the least significant.
313///
314/// Returns an unsigned 64-bit integer assembled from the bytes in little-endian
315/// order.
316///
317/// Throws a panic if the View is less than 8 bytes long or if trying to
318/// access a byte beyond the view's bounds.
319///
320/// Example:
321///
322/// ```moonbit
323/// test "View::to_uint64_le" {
324///   let bytes = b"\x01\x02\x03\x04\x05\x06\x07\x08"[:]
325///   inspect!(bytes.to_uint64_le(), content="578437695752307201")
326/// }
327/// 
328/// test "panic View::to_uint64_le/short_view" {
329///   let bytes = b"\x01\x02\x03"[:]
330///   ignore(bytes.to_uint64_le()) // Panics: view is too short
331/// }
332/// ```
333pub fn 
struct View {
  bytes: Bytes
  start: Int
  len: Int
}
A @bytes.View represents a view into a section of a Bytes without copying the data.
Example
let bs = b"\x00\x01\x02\x03\x04\x05"
let bv = bs[1:4]
assert_eq!(bv.length(), 3)
assert_eq!(bv[0], b'\x01')
assert_eq!(bv[1], b'\x02')
assert_eq!(bv[2], b'\x03')
View::
(View) -> UInt64
Converts an 8-byte sequence to an unsigned 64-bit integer using little-endian
byte order. Each byte in the view is treated as an 8-bit unsigned integer and
combined to form the final 64-bit value, with the least significant byte
first.
Parameters:
    

  • bytes_view : A view into a byte sequence that must be exactly 8 bytes
long. Each byte represents one byte of the resulting 64-bit integer, with the
first byte being the least significant.
    • 

Returns an unsigned 64-bit integer assembled from the bytes in little-endian
order.
Throws a panic if the View is less than 8 bytes long or if trying to
access a byte beyond the view's bounds.
Example:
test "View::to_uint64_le" {
  let bytes = b"\x01\x02\x03\x04\x05\x06\x07\x08"[:]
  inspect!(bytes.to_uint64_le(), content="578437695752307201")
}

test "panic View::to_uint64_le/short_view" {
  let bytes = b"\x01\x02\x03"[:]
  ignore(bytes.to_uint64_le()) // Panics: view is too short
}

Throws a panic if the index is out of bounds (less than 0 or greater than or
equal to the length of the view).
Example:
test "View::unsafe_get" {
  let bytes = b"\x01\x02\x03\x04\x05"
  let view = bytes[2:4] // view contains [0x03, 0x04]
  inspect!(view.unsafe_get(0), content="b'\\x03'")
}

test "panic View::unsafe_get/out_of_bounds" {
  let view = b"\x01\x02\x03"[:]
  ignore(view.unsafe_get(3)) // Panic: index out of bounds
}
